  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choosing how to deploy a vector database is one of the first infrastructure decisions in a RAG or semantic search system. The managed vs self-hosted split is not just about cost — it determines where your data lives, how much engineering effort you carry, and how much control you have over the index at query time. This document maps out the decision space concretely, covering the leading options in each category and the code patterns that connect them to Claude."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Side-by-side deployment comparison: Managed (Pinecone, Weaviate Cloud, Zilliz) shows your app calling a vendor-managed HTTPS API that handles load balancing, sharding, replication, auto-scaling, backups, and monitoring. Pros: zero ops, auto-scales, HA. Cons: data leaves your infra, higher cost at scale, vendor lock-in. Self-Hosted (Qdrant, Weaviate, Milvus, pgvector) shows your app calling infrastructure in your own VPC over a private network. Pros: data stays in VPC, lower cost at scale, co-located. Cons: ops burden, manual scaling, you own backups."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Core Trade-off"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Managed services let you ship faster by handing off all operational complexity — replication, index persistence, hardware provisioning, upgrade windows. Self-hosted keeps data on your infrastructure, eliminates per-query pricing, and lets you tune index parameters (HNSW "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "m"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "ef_construction"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") without constraints. Neither is universally better; the right choice depends on your scale, compliance posture, and team size."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Managed Vector Databases"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pinecone"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pinecone was the first purpose-built managed vector database to reach production readiness at scale. It offers a serverless tier (pay per query, no idle cost) and a pod-based tier (dedicated hardware with predictable latency). The API is minimal by design: upsert vectors, query top-K, optionally filter by metadata."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pinecone\nimport anthropic\n\npc = pinecone.Pinecone(api_key=\"your-key\")\n\n# Serverless index (us-east-1, cosine similarity, 1536 dims for most embedding models)\nindex = pc.Index(\"my-index\")\n\ndef upsert_chunks(chunks: list[dict]) -> None:\n    \"\"\"chunks: [{id, values, metadata}]\"\"\"\n    index.upsert(vectors=chunks, namespace=\"prod\")\n\ndef retrieve(query_embedding: list[float], top_k: int = 5, filter: dict = None) -> list[dict]:\n    result = index.query(\n        vector=query_embedding,\n        top_k=top_k,\n        filter=filter,          # e.g. {\"source\": {\"$eq\": \"docs\"}}\n        include_metadata=True,\n        namespace=\"prod\",\n    )\n    return [\n        {\"id\": m.id, \"score\": m.score, \"text\": m.metadata.get(\"text\", \"\")}\n        for m in result.matches\n    ]\n\ndef rag_answer(client: anthropic.Anthropic, query: str, query_embedding: list[float]) -> str:\n    chunks = retrieve(query_embedding, top_k=5)\n    context = \"\\n\\n\".join(c[\"text\"] for c in chunks)\n    response = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-opus-4-8\",\n        max_tokens=1024,\n        messages=[{\n            \"role\": \"user\",\n            \"content\": f\"Context:\\n{context}\\n\\nQuestion: {query}\",\n        }],\n    )\n    return response.content[0].text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Weaviate Cloud"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Weaviate Cloud (WCD) provides a hosted Weaviate cluster. Unlike Pinecone's flat namespace, Weaviate uses a schema with typed "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "classes"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", making it a better fit when your chunks have heterogeneous shapes (documents, code files, images). It supports hybrid BM25+vector search natively."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import weaviate\n\nclient = weaviate.connect_to_weaviate_cloud(\n    cluster_url=\"https://my-cluster.weaviate.network\",\n    auth_credentials=weaviate.auth.AuthApiKey(\"your-key\"),\n)\n\ncollection = client.collections.get(\"DocumentChunk\")\n\ndef retrieve_hybrid(query: str, query_vector: list[float], limit: int = 5):\n    result = collection.query.hybrid(\n        query=query,            # BM25 keyword term\n        vector=query_vector,    # semantic vector\n        alpha=0.5,              # 0=BM25 only, 1=vector only\n        limit=limit,\n        return_properties=[\"text\", \"source\", \"page\"],\n    )\n    return [{\"text\": o.properties[\"text\"], \"source\": o.properties[\"source\"]}\n            for o in result.objects]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Zilliz (Managed Milvus)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Zilliz is the managed service for Milvus, an open-source vector database built for billion-scale workloads. If you plan to self-host Milvus later, Zilliz is a low-friction starting point — the Python SDK is the same, so migration is a connection string change."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Self-Hosted Vector Databases"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Qdrant"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Qdrant is a Rust-based vector database designed for high-throughput similarity search. It supports rich payload filtering, named vectors (multiple embedding spaces per point), and HNSW tuning. Deploy it as a Docker container or Kubernetes StatefulSet."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from qdrant_client import QdrantClient\nfrom qdrant_client.models import Distance, VectorParams, PointStruct\n\nclient = QdrantClient(url=\"http://qdrant-service:6333\")  # internal cluster URL\n\n# Create collection once\nclient.recreate_collection(\n    collection_name=\"docs\",\n    vectors_config=VectorParams(size=1536, distance=Distance.COSINE),\n)\n\ndef upsert(points: list[dict]) -> None:\n    client.upsert(\n        collection_name=\"docs\",\n        points=[\n            PointStruct(id=p[\"id\"], vector=p[\"embedding\"], payload=p[\"metadata\"])\n            for p in points\n        ],\n    )\n\ndef search(vector: list[float], top_k: int = 5, filter_payload: dict = None):\n    from qdrant_client.models import Filter, FieldCondition, MatchValue\n    f = None\n    if filter_payload:\n        f = Filter(must=[\n            FieldCondition(key=k, match=MatchValue(value=v))\n            for k, v in filter_payload.items()\n        ])\n    hits = client.search(\n        collection_name=\"docs\",\n        query_vector=vector,\n        limit=top_k,\n        query_filter=f,\n        with_payload=True,\n    )\n    return [{\"text\": h.payload.get(\"text\"), \"score\": h.score} for h in hits]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Qdrant on Kubernetes (minimal StatefulSet)\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: StatefulSet\nmetadata:\n  name: qdrant\nspec:\n  replicas: 1\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: qdrant\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: qdrant\n        image: qdrant/qdrant:v1.9.0\n        ports:\n        - containerPort: 6333   # REST\n        - containerPort: 6334   # gRPC\n        volumeMounts:\n        - name: storage\n          mountPath: /qdrant/storage\n  volumeClaimTemplates:\n  - metadata:\n      name: storage\n    spec:\n      accessModes: [ReadWriteOnce]\n      resources:\n        requests:\n          storage: 50Gi"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "pgvector (Self-Hosted PostgreSQL)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If you already run PostgreSQL, adding pgvector keeps your stack simple: vectors live in the same database as your application data, joins are free, and you have full SQL expressiveness. The trade-off is that pgvector's IVFFlat and HNSW indexes are slower to build at hundreds of millions of vectors than purpose-built systems."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "-- Enable extension once per database\nCREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector;\n\nCREATE TABLE document_chunks (\n    id         BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    doc_id     BIGINT NOT NULL,\n    chunk_text TEXT   NOT NULL,\n    embedding  vector(1536),      -- dimension must match your embedding model\n    metadata   JSONB  NOT NULL DEFAULT '{}'\n);\n\n-- HNSW index: better recall/speed at query time, slower build\nCREATE INDEX ON document_chunks\n    USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops)\n    WITH (m = 16, ef_construction = 64);\n\n-- Cosine similarity search with SQL filter in one query\nSELECT chunk_text, 1 - (embedding <=> $1::vector) AS similarity\nFROM   document_chunks\nWHERE  metadata @> '{\"source\": \"docs\"}'\nORDER  BY embedding <=> $1::vector\nLIMIT  5;"
          }
        ]
      },
